{"id":"1801.00678","submitter":"Jordan Fran\\c{c}ois","authors":"Jordan Fran\\c{c}ois","title":"Artificial vs Substantial Gauge Symmetries: a Criterion and an\n  Application to the Electroweak Model","comments":"13 pages. Revised version accepted for publication in Philosophy of\n  Science. The author thanks the two anonymous reviewers for their valuable\n  input","journal-ref":"Philosophy of Science 86, no. 3 (July 2019): 472-496","doi":"10.1086/703571","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.hist-ph hep-th","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  To systematically answer the generalized Kretschmann objection, we propose a\nmean to make operational a criterion widely recognized as allowing to decide if\nthe gauge symmetry of a theory is artificial or substantial. Our proposition is\nbased on the dressing field method of gauge symmetry reduction, a new simple\ntool from mathematical physics. This general scheme allows in particular to\nstraightforwardly argue that the notion of spontaneous symmetry breaking is\nsuperfluous to the empirical success of the electroweak theory. Important\nquestions regarding the context of justification of the theory then arise.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 6 Nov 2017 21:16:19 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 15 Jul 2018 14:17:21 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 17 Jul 2018 16:43:49 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 31 Jan 2023 13:46:03 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-01"}
